{
  "card_id": "equal_highs",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Equal Highs",
  "aliases": [
    "failure swing highs",
    "Failure Swing Highs",
    "Relatively Equal Highs",
    "relatively equal highs",
    "stacked highs",
    "Stacked Highs"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "Two or more swing highs at approximately the same price level, forming a cluster of buy-side liquidity where resting buy stops accumulate. Price is expected to sweep these levels, acting as a draw-on-liquidity target, before reversing or continuing in the prevailing direction.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify two or more swing highs (peaks with lower highs on both sides) at approximately the same horizontal price level, forming a tight cluster with minimal vertical separation.",
    "Confirm the highs are visually aligned and rest above current price action, representing a pool of buy-side liquidity (resting buy stops).",
    "Verify that no higher time frame PD array (e.g., order block, fair value gap) sits directly overhead; if one does, classify the structure by that level instead.",
    "An imbalance (fair value gap) above the equal highs strengthens the level as a draw on liquidity.",
    "If the highs are tightly stacked without meaningful separation, treat the upper‑most high as the relevant swing high and the lower one(s) as failure swings; do not anticipate a reversal from a lower high before the upper high is swept.",
    "Apply a three‑higher‑time‑frame‑candle look‑back period to determine relevance (e.g., 3 months on daily, 3 days on hourly charts).",
    "On instruments where price frequently sweeps slightly beyond equal highs (e.g., oil), allow a wider tolerance when identifying the exact level.",
    "Monitor for price approach and subsequent sweep of the level, which acts as a liquidity grab; then look for displacement or reversal signals (e.g., change in state of delivery, V‑shaped reversal) after the sweep."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Equal highs act as a draw on liquidity and a price magnet, representing a cluster of buy-side stops expected to be swept. They serve as profit targets in bullish scenarios or as the manipulation leg before a bearish reversal. Entries are taken after the sweep, confirmed by a change in state of delivery, displacement lower, or a V‑shaped/reversal candle (e.g., candle 2 or 3 closure). Stop losses should account for the sweep, especially in assets like oil where a wider tolerance is needed. Do not short directly into equal highs; wait for the sweep and confirmation of direction.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering a trade targeting equal highs after price has already reached them and reversed, rather than while price is still trading away from the level.",
    "Treating equal highs as standalone patterns without confirming context (e.g., sweep of opposing liquidity, closure back inside the higher time frame range).",
    "Shorting into equal highs without waiting for the sweep to occur first.",
    "Trusting a reversal from a lower equal high before the upper (relevant) high is swept.",
    "Anticipating a reversal at equal highs without waiting for a confirmed signal (e.g., change in state of delivery, displacement lower, candle 2 or 3 closure, V‑shaped reversal).",
    "Treating a series of up‑close candles that formed equal highs as a valid order block when no higher time frame PD array sits above them.",
    "Failing to check higher time frames to see if equal highs are part of a larger liquidity structure.",
    "Using a stop loss that is too tight directly above the equal highs, especially in volatile instruments like oil where a wider sweep is common.",
    "Allowing price to retrace too deeply (e.g., into a lower fair value gap) before expecting expansion into equal highs, thereby invalidating the bullish premise.",
    "Confusing single old swing highs with equal high clusters, which carry different liquidity implications.",
    "Using equal highs that fall outside the three‑higher‑time‑frame‑candle look‑back period, assuming they are still relevant."
  ],
